    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks for the info. you mentioned magnesium or iron though. how do i know if it's specifically nitrogen? i've heard nitrogen deficiency makes the bottom leaves yellow primero. also what kind of stuff should i actually add to the dirt to get the nitrogen back up?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "You're right, a nitrogen deficiency can cause yellowing leaves, especially on the lower stems. This is because nitrogen is essential for leaf growth and development, and a lack of it can lead to stunted or wilted leaves. However, in the case of tomatoes, a nitrogen deficiency is less common than other nutrient deficiencies.\n\nTo confirm whether it's a nitrogen deficiency, look for other signs such as stunted growth, pale leaves, or a lack of fruiting. If you notice these symptoms, a nitrogen-rich fertilizer might be a good idea.\n\nAs for adding nitrogen to the soil, you can use a balanced fertilizer that contains nitrogen, phosphorus, and potassium (NPK). A general-purpose fertilizer with a ratio of 10-10-10 NPK should provide a good starting point. You can also consider adding organic matter like compost or manure to the soil, as these can provide a slow release of nitrogen.\n\nHowever, if you're looking for a more targeted approach, you can try adding a nitrogen-rich fertilizer specifically formulated for tomatoes, such as ammonium nitrate or urea. These products are often used to promote fruiting and flowering in tomato plants.\n\nIt's worth noting that over-fertilizing can be just as bad",
      "source": "target",
